797
01:02:28,160 --> 01:02:34,640
You can say things to one another and not have to hide behind like I think most people will opt into it and if you opt into it,

798
01:02:34,640 --> 01:02:36,319
everything gets easier down the road.

799
01:02:36,319 --> 01:02:40,799
So the first thing is get everyone to opt in that like this is the kind of relationship that we want to have.

800
01:02:40,799 --> 01:02:51,200
One trickle throw out that uh I've heard that worked really well along these same lines is asking people would you prefer do you prefer feedback in the moment or do you prefer it kind of uh every once

801
01:02:51,200 --> 01:03:00,480
in everyone every month or or every week or something like that and everyone's like no no in the moment and just like tell me as soon as something happens and then that gives you that freedom to just okay yeah let me give you feedback here.

802
01:03:00,480 --> 01:03:00,720
>> Yeah.

803
01:03:00,720 --> 01:03:06,400
So if you get people to opt in yes I want us to have a great relationship I want us to help each other get better.

804
01:03:06,400 --> 01:03:07,680
I want feedback.

805
01:03:07,680 --> 01:03:13,280
That's 60% of the hard part of delivering difficult feedback later on.

806
01:03:13,280 --> 01:03:19,839
So then the second tactic I will say is that when you actually give the feedback, it helps a lot.

807
01:03:19,839 --> 01:03:29,359
First you have to check am I actually giving this feedback because it's in the spirit of trying to help one another.

808
01:03:29,359 --> 01:03:35,440
And if the answer is yes, then we're we've like, you know, moved from 60% to 80%.

809
01:03:35,440 --> 01:03:37,119
It's going to go well, right?

810
01:03:37,119 --> 01:03:43,839
But what can often happen is I'm feeling like something happens, you do something, it triggers me because I don't know,

811
01:03:43,839 --> 01:03:51,680
I had like a bad experience about that type of thing before and I'm kind of feeling mad and I want to be right.

812
01:03:51,680 --> 01:03:58,559
Like if my my real rationale for why I want to give you feedback is I want to validate myself.

813
01:03:58,559 --> 01:04:00,000
I want to be right.

814
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:02,640
I want to tell you you're wrong.

815
01:04:02,640 --> 01:04:04,480
I want to punish you.

816
01:04:04,480 --> 01:04:05,839
It's not going to go well.

817
01:04:05,839 --> 01:04:07,119
it's just already there.

818
01:04:07,119 --> 01:04:12,720
It's there's no way you can deliver it and somehow unless you're a tremendous actor,

819
01:04:12,720 --> 01:04:14,640
um it's just not going to go well.

820
01:04:14,640 --> 01:04:16,880
So, you have to first check your intention.

821
01:04:16,880 --> 01:04:18,799
But if you've done that, you're like, "No, no, no.

822
01:04:18,799 --> 01:04:19,440
I thought about it.

823
01:04:19,440 --> 01:04:20,319
I'm calm now.

824
01:04:20,319 --> 01:04:22,319
I'm not like see seeing red.

825
01:04:22,319 --> 01:04:30,240
I really think that Lenny is just not aware that when he says this, it makes me and other people feel left out or whatever it is,

826
01:04:30,240 --> 01:04:30,960
right?"

827
01:04:30,960 --> 01:04:33,599
Then I need to be able to give it to you.

828
01:04:33,599 --> 01:04:38,160
And so usually then if you're like, "Okay, now I might be nervous because I don't want to offend you.

829
01:04:38,160 --> 01:04:39,680
I really value our relationship.

830
01:04:39,680 --> 01:04:43,520
How am I going to tell you, you know, I don't want you to get defensive."

831
01:04:43,520 --> 01:04:47,680
What then the third tactic I have is just say that out loud.

832
01:04:47,680 --> 01:04:58,960
Like if I sit down with you and I say, "Lenny, I'm so nervous right now is I want to give you some feedback and I'm really worried that it's going to impact our relationship and I so value our

833
01:04:58,960 --> 01:05:06,799
relationship and I don't want that to happen, but I also feel like >> it's just going to help you to hear it if you can."

834
01:05:06,799 --> 01:05:10,640
That does so much of the work of of it's it's humanizing, right?

835
01:05:10,640 --> 01:05:14,240
It's like you're going to be you're going to realize that I'm going out on a limb.

836
01:05:14,240 --> 01:05:24,720
I'm being really vulnerable and likely you're going to hear that so much more than if I just find a way to like drop it like just like lobby it over

837
01:05:24,720 --> 01:05:25,839
because it's so difficult.

838
01:05:25,839 --> 01:05:33,440
Just actually lean into the fact that it is difficult and expose that because that builds a lot of human connection.

839
01:05:33,440 --> 01:05:35,039
>> This is amazing advice.

840
01:05:35,039 --> 01:05:36,799
Very tactical.

841
01:05:36,799 --> 01:05:37,520
Okay.

842
01:05:37,520 --> 01:05:38,960
Uh is there anything else?

843
01:05:38,960 --> 01:05:44,480
So, we've talked about a bunch of timeless pieces of manager wisdom, things that people need to hear,

844
01:05:44,480 --> 01:05:45,920
especially as new managers.

845
01:05:45,920 --> 01:05:53,200
Is there anything else that you think is really important that I think people are just not fully groing for being great managers?

846
01:05:53,200 --> 01:05:58,480
>> I think the idea of win-win, I think about that all the time in my mind.

847
01:05:58,480 --> 01:06:05,359
And I go back to because I think that often we have this story in our heads that sometimes things are adversarial.

848
01:06:05,359 --> 01:06:10,000
As a manager, I'm trying to get people to be more productive.

849
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:13,920
So, I'm trying to get them to do a thing that maybe they don't want to do.

850
01:06:13,920 --> 01:06:20,160
I'm going to try and get them to work harder or I'm going to um somehow put more pressure on them.

851
01:06:20,160 --> 01:06:24,640
Like, if you start thinking like that, that's not a win-win way to be thinking, right?

852
01:06:24,640 --> 01:06:32,880
That's like you saying my getting better outcomes has to come at the expense of somebody else losing something.

853
01:06:32,880 --> 01:06:40,079
Um, and I think if you start thinking like that, it's very difficult to come up with a strategy or to truly be successful.

854
01:06:40,079 --> 01:06:45,200
But if you say, "Look, actually my job is to figure out how to create win-wins."

855
01:06:45,200 --> 01:06:56,799
So, I actually don't want I don't want somebody over the long run um to feel like what I've done is just create a ton of pressure for them and now they're super burnt out and they're quick because that's not good

856
01:06:56,799 --> 01:06:57,280
for our team.

857
01:06:57,280 --> 01:06:58,000
That's not good for me.

858
01:06:58,000 --> 01:07:00,880
That's not good for our long-term relationship.

859
01:07:00,880 --> 01:07:05,599
How do we find a like how do we find the solution that can be win-win?

860
01:07:05,599 --> 01:07:08,480
And I think if you think like that, a lot of things get easier.

861
01:07:08,480 --> 01:07:12,400
So, for example, with new managers, I think this is true for me too.

862
01:07:12,400 --> 01:07:20,400
The first time I had to tell someone that they're not they shouldn't be a part of this team was extremely fraught for me.

863
01:07:20,400 --> 01:07:31,440
And the main reason was because I'm putting myself in their shoes and I'm imagining that this is truly horrible and I've just done a huge disservice to this person and that's like the most

864
01:07:31,440 --> 01:07:32,720
awful thing.

865
01:07:32,720 --> 01:07:39,599
But there's another way to look at it which is hey if this person's on the team they probably want to be successful.

866
01:07:39,599 --> 01:07:40,960
They want to do great work.

867
01:07:40,960 --> 01:07:42,000
They want to be valued.

868
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:43,599
They want to grow their career.

869
01:07:43,599 --> 01:07:53,359
if this is not the place for them because it doesn't align with their true interests and the things that are going to help them be successful is just not the thing that

870
01:07:53,359 --> 01:07:55,440
they either want to do or can do.

871
01:07:55,440 --> 01:08:02,559
Um, at this point, it doesn't do that person any good for me to somehow try to continue to make it.

872
01:08:02,559 --> 01:08:03,760
It's actually going to be miserable.

873
01:08:03,760 --> 01:08:06,640
Like I'm going back to like prolonging that misery state.

874
01:08:06,640 --> 01:08:10,400
And so sometimes a win-win thing is to just say, "Look, it's not working.

875
01:08:10,400 --> 01:08:18,799
And I know I I respect and value you so much that I know you want to do something that you can be proud of and you can grow in and that's going to be really valued.

876
01:08:18,799 --> 01:08:21,920
And right here, what we got, this isn't it.

877
01:08:21,920 --> 01:08:30,480
That's like a win-win way of looking at the situation, not a like, you know, oh my firing them is just definitely going to be a horrible,

878
01:08:30,480 --> 01:08:32,239
you know, I'm not trying to say it's not going to be hard.

879
01:08:32,239 --> 01:08:38,239
Obviously, it's hard, but it's in the in the the mentality and the the the mental model,

880
01:08:38,239 --> 01:08:42,159
I think, makes all the difference because it's going to be different in the way that I convey it to them.

881
01:08:42,159 --> 01:08:53,440
It's going to be different in why this actually in the grander scheme of things may be great and it's going to reduce this adversarial feeling where they're now going to see me as like an enemy or

882
01:08:53,440 --> 01:08:59,359
somebody with all this power who's making, you know, uh choices that impact them and they feel powerless.

883
01:08:59,359 --> 01:09:01,120
It has to be a collaboration.

884
01:09:01,120 --> 01:09:03,120
And I think if it's not win-win, if and I could be wrong.

885
01:09:03,120 --> 01:09:04,640
I would say, "I don't think it's right."

886
01:09:04,640 --> 01:09:06,960
The person could actually say, "No, you're wrong."

887
01:09:06,960 --> 01:09:12,400
And that would actually be great information because then maybe we can go back and we can find a way to make it win-win.

888
01:09:12,400 --> 01:09:14,480
>> Yeah, I was just going to say they have to believe this.

889
01:09:14,480 --> 01:09:16,159
You can't just s make it sound like this.

890
01:09:16,159 --> 01:09:16,880
Here's the win.

891
01:09:16,880 --> 01:09:17,679
You're getting let go.

892
01:09:17,679 --> 01:09:19,040
It's a huge win for you.

893
01:09:19,040 --> 01:09:22,400
>> Uh but in reality, the way you phrased it is actually almost always true.

894
01:09:22,400 --> 01:09:27,120
Like this is just not a place that you will be happy and succeed at, and it's better you go do something else.

895
01:09:27,120 --> 01:09:28,159
>> Yeah.

896
01:09:28,159 --> 01:09:28,560
>> Okay.

897
01:09:28,560 --> 01:09:32,080
I'm going to keep fishing in this pool to see what else we got, but when we run out,

898
01:09:32,080 --> 01:09:32,480
let me know.

899
01:09:32,480 --> 01:09:41,520
Is there anything else that you think people should know, should hear, especially new managers that um they're still not fully getting?

900
01:09:41,520 --> 01:09:49,199
>> I think being aware of PE your own energy and conviction is really really important.

901
01:09:49,199 --> 01:09:59,760
So I go back like a lot of these themes as you can see go back to like you have to first understand this about yourself and have the right mindset and when you do it becomes much easier to be able to be impactful with

902
01:09:59,760 --> 01:10:00,800
other people.

903
01:10:00,800 --> 01:10:02,800
So this is another one.

904
01:10:02,800 --> 01:10:14,400
I think it's very difficult for managers to be able, you know, we talked a lot about the three pillars of what are the the major um uh tools of a manager,

905
01:10:14,400 --> 01:10:14,640
right?

906
01:10:14,640 --> 01:10:15,520
The first is people.

907
01:10:15,520 --> 01:10:21,360
And so we talked a lot about like the importance of dimensionality and feedback and helping reflect and grow people.

908
01:10:21,360 --> 01:10:24,800
I think the second one is around purpose.

909
01:10:24,800 --> 01:10:26,400
Purpose is like what are we here to do?

910
01:10:26,400 --> 01:10:27,920
What's our northstar?

911
01:10:27,920 --> 01:10:33,760
And I think it's very hard to actually convey that if you don't have conviction yourself.

912
01:10:33,760 --> 01:10:44,960
And so watching your conviction is really important particularly since a lot of people who are managers you often start out not as like the founder and the CEO of the company but you you might be like the middle manager.

913
01:10:44,960 --> 01:10:54,560
So in some ways you don't you didn't like create the vision but you are in some ways expected to execute it or take a piece of it and do it.

914
01:10:54,560 --> 01:11:00,640
And I find that sometimes what new managers don't pay attention to enough is what is their true belief.

915
01:11:00,640 --> 01:11:03,679
Like they feel like they might have to be like a soldier.

916
01:11:03,679 --> 01:11:06,159
So they just get orders and they have to execute it.

917
01:11:06,159 --> 01:11:14,719
But it really makes a difference if they themselves have gone through the work of of of thinking through wait why are we doing this?

918
01:11:14,719 --> 01:11:16,320
Does do I believe this strategy?

919
01:11:16,320 --> 01:11:18,000
Does it make sense or not?

920
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:23,679
And if it doesn't make sense to go and actually have the conversation with, you know,

921
01:11:23,679 --> 01:11:35,440
their manager or whoever else just so they un they can get to alignment on like I really believe in what I'm doing because if you don't really believe in what you're doing and or you're just kind of paring the thing that got passed

922
01:11:35,440 --> 01:11:47,280
through the organization, it's very hard for you to then be able to help other people see what that magic is or to be actually really effective as as a person who can hold that vision and that

923
01:11:47,280 --> 01:11:47,920
purpose.

924
01:11:47,920 --> 01:11:54,560
So, I just think you have to really check in with yourself on like, wait, I I know we're told to do this and this is what we have to do,

925
01:11:54,560 --> 01:11:56,400
but how do we really feel about it?

926
01:11:56,400 --> 01:12:01,679
Because if you don't feel good about it, then it's not going to be very likely that the project's going to succeed.

927
01:12:01,679 --> 01:12:06,080
I can tell you right now, every single manager I've ever managed where they're like,

928
01:12:06,080 --> 01:12:08,000
I don't really think this is a good idea.

929
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:13,040
The there's no case where I can think of where the project somehow turned out to be like wildly successful.

930
01:12:13,040 --> 01:12:19,360
This is such a classic challenge of managers is getting things done that you don't really agree with.

931
01:12:19,360 --> 01:12:27,360
And uh I can't help but ask you for advice on someone that isn't that but in that place of just okay we have this feature our co is prioritizing.

932
01:12:27,360 --> 01:12:35,120
I just this is not a good idea but I need to have a brave face and not make it sound like I'm just being told what to do and I'm just reporting orders.

933
01:12:35,120 --> 01:12:36,320
I I don't believe in this.

934
01:12:36,320 --> 01:12:37,199
Like you don't want to do that.

935
01:12:37,199 --> 01:12:41,520
You become a terrible unsuccessful manager and you people lose trust in you.

936
01:12:41,520 --> 01:12:44,800
What's your advice to folks that are in that place of just how to find that balance?

937
01:12:44,800 --> 01:12:51,760
>> So, I think first if you feel that way, you got to actually find a way to get it out and and engage in dialogue.

938
01:12:51,760 --> 01:12:55,360
So, if you're like, I think my manager told me to do this, I think it's a terrible idea.

939
01:12:55,360 --> 01:13:02,080
You got to talk to your manager about it or you got to talk to the CEO or whoever and feel because once you engage in a dialogue,

940
01:13:02,080 --> 01:13:09,920
what will often happen is you'll learn more like you'll have new information, you'll have new assumptions and maybe you'll have influenced a project in some manner.

941
01:13:09,920 --> 01:13:21,199
But often the more you can learn about okay why did some other smart people feel like we should do this and what parts of it do I believe and what parts am I more skeptical about like you can probably

942
01:13:21,199 --> 01:13:32,880
decompose it and from a blanket it's good or bad to like okay there's this is a hypothesis this is a hypothesis is a hypothesis I might kind of believe this one the reason I don't like the proposal

943
01:13:32,880 --> 01:13:43,440
I don't believe this particular hypothesis but I believe these other ones right and so when you can start to get one level deeper into breaking it down into a set of assumptions that

944
01:13:43,440 --> 01:13:54,560
makes it much easier because then you'll likely find something that you do kind of resonate with and you might be able to then steer things like okay that hypothesis doesn't you can't I I believe and disagree and commit but now we can

945
01:13:54,560 --> 01:14:04,000
be very specific we can isolate the thing that like and and what we can also often do is like okay the reason I didn't like this proposal is because I

946
01:14:04,000 --> 01:14:11,600
have this this like I believe that this assumption is wrong right so for and they come up with like a really stupid example,

947
01:14:11,600 --> 01:14:15,360
but you know, your suggestion is I know we have a great idea.

948
01:14:15,360 --> 01:14:18,239
We're going to go and put a lemonade stand on every block.

949
01:14:18,239 --> 01:14:20,960
And my core assumption is people do not like lemonade.

950
01:14:20,960 --> 01:14:22,640
That's not the hot beverage right now.

951
01:14:22,640 --> 01:14:25,280
And so I there therefore I think this is stupid plan.

952
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:29,360
But if I talk to you about it and you're like, "No, no, this is the core assumption we disagree on."

953
01:14:29,360 --> 01:14:33,520
Likely what starts to unfold is like, "Well, let's just can we get some data?

954
01:14:33,520 --> 01:14:34,640
Can we get some information?

955
01:14:34,640 --> 01:14:38,960
like can we just is there a quicker way to validate whether people like lemonade?

956
01:14:38,960 --> 01:14:45,840
Perhaps we should just test it in one market before we go and open up the lemonade stands across the entire 50 states.

957
01:14:45,840 --> 01:14:51,600
And so what happens is we can likely get to the actual specific area and come up with something.

958
01:14:51,600 --> 01:14:56,880
And then if I have to now share with my team, you know, we're going to try this hypothesis.

959
01:14:56,880 --> 01:15:00,560
I'm not sure how I feel about it, but I actually do think like I don't know for sure.

960
01:15:00,560 --> 01:15:12,320
And you know, our our CEO seems to think this is but we're just going to test it and we're going to do the test in a way where that's what we want to find out is like do people really love like do 18 to 25 year olds

961
01:15:12,320 --> 01:15:24,000
love lemonade if we put them on these neighborhood what college campuses right so it becomes very specific and everyone's like well yeah I'm I don't know for sure but like I'm happy to go and and test that and and commit to it.

962
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:25,040
This is such a good advice.

963
01:15:25,040 --> 01:15:26,880
And there's also you could layer on.

964
01:15:26,880 --> 01:15:28,880
Here's the things I do agree with and believe.

965
01:15:28,880 --> 01:15:31,440
Here's the ways that I see this as totally right.

966
01:15:31,440 --> 01:15:34,960
Here's the piece that I'm not so sure about, but that's why we're going to run this test.

967
01:15:34,960 --> 01:15:39,600
And here's why it's the smallest version of this test and why it's a great idea just to figure it out.

968
01:15:39,600 --> 01:15:41,440
And we'll we'll show them.

969
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:43,679
I mean, you probably don't want to say that.

970
01:15:43,679 --> 01:15:45,840
Uh, as you give this answer, it's so interesting.

971
01:15:45,840 --> 01:15:50,800
I almost want to do a whole new episode with you later of just like common conundrums managers have,

972
01:15:50,800 --> 01:15:55,520
challenges that every manager runs into that are really difficult to figure out on the spot.

973
01:15:55,520 --> 01:15:57,280
We could save that for the future.

